So there are benefits
to being a good citizen,

00:04:29.950 --> 00:04:31.830
but there are also responsibilities,
clearly, right?

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:35.420
We need to be law-abiding citizens,
which we all probably are, hopefully.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:38.390
And your application needs
to be a law-abiding citizen,

00:04:38.390 --> 00:04:39.170
so to speak.

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:41.680
So let's talk through some
of these responsibilities.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:44.530
There are three areas of
responsibility that your

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:46.650
application has on the platform.

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:49.530
And essentially,
they boil down to the basics,

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:51.110
which we'll talk about.

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:55.050
They boil down to behaviors,
implementing the behaviors that are

00:04:55.050 --> 00:04:56.760
unique to the world of Mac OS X.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:04:59.460
And the appearance of Mac OS X.

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:02.760
Does your application follow that
appearance and adhere to that appearance?

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:05.180
So what are the basics?

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.030
By the basics I mean,
and these are basics that aren't

00:05:08.030 --> 00:05:11.380
even specific to Aqua so much as
they are specific to the Macintosh.

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:14.620
What does it take to make a, you know,
what are the characteristics

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:16.180
of a Macintosh application?

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:19.460
And believe it or not,
there are violations of these

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:22.780
and we'll have a lot of fun
looking at some of them.

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:26.490
So I want to start with one of
the most basic characteristics

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:28.620
of a Mac application.

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:30.840
And that is that the
application has menus,

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:31.350
right?

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:34.190
And that the menus are
structured in the proper format.

00:05:34.210 --> 00:05:38.440
And the menu layout for Mac OS X is such
that if we're starting on the very left,

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:40.860
we have the Apple menu,
which is system global.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:43.240
It's for commands that
relate to the system.

00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:47.150
It is, it enables the user to do
stuff to the system regardless

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:48.880
of what context they're in,
regardless of what

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:49.720
application they're running.

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:53.040
They can sleep the system or do whatever,
you know, go to system preferences.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:56.750
And the Apple menu is really
not for application developers.

00:05:57.170 --> 00:05:59.330
Moving right,
we have the application menu.

00:05:59.330 --> 00:06:01.100
This is where you start
to get interested,

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:04.210
because the application menu deals
with the commands that are specific

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:07.840
to your application as a whole,
as a whole entity.

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:11.160
This is where you put things like quit,
because we quit applications now.

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:13.650
We don't quit files
like we did in the past.

00:06:13.910 --> 00:06:15.560
This is where you put
your app preferences,

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.080
because preferences apply
to the whole application.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:23.010
And this is where you put anything that
relates to your application as a whole.

00:06:23.770 --> 00:06:25.260
Moving right from that,
we have the file menu,

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:27.330
document specific commands.

00:06:27.490 --> 00:06:30.730
This is where you put any command
that relates to your documents,

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:32.750
the documents that your
application manages.

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:35.850
So we open documents, we print them,
we save them, etc.

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:38.530
That's where they all go,
those types of commands

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:39.760
go in the file menu.

00:06:40.270 --> 00:06:42.670
Moving right from that,
remember there's this hierarchy, right?

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.740
We've got system, global,
the whole system.

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:47.090
Then we've got the application
that runs on the system,

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:47.650
commands.

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:50.620
Then we've got the commands
that relate to the documents

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:51.860
that application manages.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:54.100
And then to the right of that,
we've got edit menu,

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:56.920
the edit menu which affects
the content of your documents.

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:59.790
And then to the right of that,
you might have some other specific

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.320
menus for your application.

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:04.320
But remember,
those menus should contain commands that

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:06.520
affect the content of your documents.

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:08.860
So that there's this inherent hierarchy
that users begin to understand as

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:10.150
they move through the application.

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:14.840
And following the
application-specific menus,

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:19.240
we've got the window
menu and the help menu.

00:07:19.240 --> 00:07:22.750
The window menu in Jaguar, in fact,
contains some new functionality,

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:26.000
which is the ability to cycle
through your active document windows

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.260
using command-tilde on the keyboard.

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.370
And the help menu is where you
would put your access to your help

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:34.240
book and your user assistance,
your online help.

00:07:34.300 --> 00:07:38.000
As we're talking about menus,
I want to talk about another fundamental

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:40.020
basic for a Macintosh application.

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:44.900
And that is respecting or
adhering to the reserved keyboard

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:47.480
equivalents that we've set out in
the Aqua human interface guidelines.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.660
We all use the Mac.

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:53.700
We're all used to, without even thinking,
doing command-s to save, you know,

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:57.800
printing, cut, copy, paste, undo,
all of these things.

00:07:57.800 --> 00:07:58.630
We don't even think about it.

00:07:58.660 --> 00:08:00.320
Our hands just go down to
the keyboard and we do the

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:02.040
appropriate keyboard equivalent,
right?

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:06.100
Here we've got an example of a
shipping application on 10 that has

00:08:06.130 --> 00:08:08.580
completely ignored these guidelines.

00:08:08.580 --> 00:08:12.770
And the effect is... that if I start
to use this application as a user,

00:08:12.790 --> 00:08:14.860
I start to use those familiar
keyboard equivalents,

00:08:14.890 --> 00:08:15.340
right?

00:08:17.690 --> 00:08:19.770
And I'm going to be stymied
because it's going to do things

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:23.180
that are completely beyond what
I would have expected it to do.

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:25.240
And in session one we
talked about expectations.

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:28.340
And suddenly I'm going to use
this product and now it behaves

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:31.780
in a way that's very different
than what I expected it to do.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:36.200
We've got command P for preview, A,
which should be select all,

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:40.450
does something else, S,
does scan instead of save, etc.

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:43.640
So as you bring your
application to Mac OS X,

00:08:43.640 --> 00:08:46.960
if you're coming from Windows or Java,
there are many of you

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:47.840
that are doing that.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:50.460
Even if you're writing
custom in-house applications,

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:56.340
it's important to use the reserved
command keys in the appropriate manner.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:08:59.200
Because it means that as users
move from your application to

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:02.450
another or from another to yours,
some of these basic behaviors

00:09:02.550 --> 00:09:03.560
are going to be there.

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:06.370
And they're going to have this
level of consistency between

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:08.030
the usage of the applications.

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:09.750
And it'll mean that
they're very comfortable.

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:17.160
Another basic thing that your application
should do is have your windows appear

00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:20.260
and operate the way other windows
appear and operate in the system.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:24.780
Mac OS X introduces this
layering model of interleaved

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:29.550
windows between applications,
and windows have a unique appearance,

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:31.070
they minimize to the dock, etc.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:33.270
Your windows should behave the same way.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:43.210
The only constraint in the world
of Mac OS X is the desktop.

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:46.250
The Mac OS X desktop might
span multiple monitors,

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.240
but they are constrained in that area.

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:55.150
However, there are applications that
are being brought to Mac OS X

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:30.270
very different behavior and suddenly the
user is faced with a situation that's,

00:10:30.270 --> 00:10:33.960
you know, very foreign to them in terms
of how the overall system works.

00:10:34.010 --> 00:10:37.600
So the right way for this to be
done on Mac OS X would be to drop

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:41.350
the MDI interface and basically put
those document windows on the overall

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:44.380
desktop and let them behave like
any other standard document window.

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:47.460
And if you're a Java developer
and this is an issue for you,

00:10:47.460 --> 00:10:49.780
there's documentation on
our developer website,

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.620
I believe,
certainly contact developer technical

00:10:51.620 --> 00:10:53.020
support to get assistance with that.

00:10:53.370 --> 00:10:56.360
Contact me, we'll give you the assistance
you need to solve this problem

00:10:56.360 --> 00:10:58.380
because it is solvable.

00:10:58.380 --> 00:10:59.770
And I don't mean to say
that Java developers are

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:00.540
the only ones doing this.

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:02.530
There are other people who are
doing this occasionally as well.

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:07.370
Another basic,
basic thing that you need to

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:10.710
do bringing your application to
Mac OS X is build upon system controls.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:14.530
We are doing our best to
extend the control set that

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:15.570
we have available to you.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:19.010
And so in most cases,
there's really no need to

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:22.350
customize the behavior of controls
or create your own controls.

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:24.360
There are instances
where that is necessary,

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:27.720
and so I would encourage you to
work with me to get an understanding

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:30.200
of that so that I can champion
that for you within engineering.

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:33.860
But building upon the standard system
controls means you're going to get

00:11:33.930 --> 00:11:36.000
the right appearance for one thing.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.530
But secondly,
you're going to inherit for free much

00:11:38.530 --> 00:11:42.200
of the behavior that we're talking
about in terms of universal access.

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:44.670
So the keyboard navigation
will come for free.

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:48.190
Speaking back of the items below
the mouse will come for free.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:50.520
You know, focus rings,
all that will come for free provided

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:52.440
you use the standard system controls.

00:11:52.440 --> 00:11:55.170
If you don't use the system
controls but draw controls

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:58.320
yourself using Appearance Manager,
for example, in Carbon,

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:01.760
it means you're going to have
a little... not only a little,

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:04.290
but in some cases,
you're going to have a lot more

00:12:04.290 --> 00:12:08.110
work to do to implement the same
behaviors that you could get for free.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:13.050
So I encourage you to use standard
system controls wherever possible.

00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:17.860
And on that topic, I want to just, it's,
you know, it's my honor to announce the

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:20.200
fact that the combo box control,
which has always been

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:22.360
available to Cocoa to date,
is now available for Carbon.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:25.810
And we'll look at a couple examples
later on of where that's being used

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:27.920
to greatly simplify some dialogues.

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:31.400
And there are the APIs for you.

