locations for storing music and pictures,

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:51.450
you know, everything that's listed there,
movies, et cetera.

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:55.200
If your application is a
content creating application,

00:13:55.210 --> 00:13:58.460
you should default to the
appropriate location for saving

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:01.190
documents from within your product.

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:04.100
And while we're on this topic,
let's talk about the documents folder,

00:14:04.100 --> 00:14:06.900
which is part of every logged
in user's home directory.

00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:09.480
The documents folder is another
area where we're seeing some

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:12.390
difficulty with applications.

00:14:12.630 --> 00:14:18.390
It is reserved exclusively for
documents that users create.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:22.590
So where a user is inside of a document
in your application and says save

00:14:22.610 --> 00:14:25.240
and puts it in the documents folder,
that's the document that

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:26.690
they explicitly created.

00:14:26.870 --> 00:14:29.300
Everything else that's
related to your application,

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:33.180
that's sort of vaguely user created
in the sense that it might be a mail

00:14:33.180 --> 00:14:37.500
database or it's a contacts database or
it's some other thing that you really--

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:42.000
is necessary for application support
does not belong in the documents folder.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:43.800
It should be put in
the library directory,

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:45.400
library folder.

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:50.750
So--and the side--sort of side issue on
that is training your users through your

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:53.840
documentation or through tech support,
et cetera, that if they back up

00:14:53.860 --> 00:14:56.540
their world on Mac OS X,
they need to back up more than

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:57.690
just their documents folder.

00:14:57.700 --> 00:14:59.910
They need to back up their
whole home directory because

00:14:59.910 --> 00:15:02.630
it contains preferences,
it contains application support

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:05.380
files that are important,
important, and it also as well

00:15:05.390 --> 00:15:07.430
contains their documents.

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:10.960
So those are the basics,
and I don't mean to imply

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:12.700
that those are the basics.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:14.500
I mean, they're the basics I'm
talking about today,

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:16.750
but there's a whole pile of other
stuff I could have talked about,

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.120
but in the interest of time,
those are the ones I wanted to

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:21.610
touch on specifically because
those are the ones that I see the

00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:26.980
most difficulty with developers
implementing those on Mac OS X.

00:15:26.980 --> 00:15:28.880
Let's talk about behaviors.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:33.120
You have responsibilities as a
citizen on Mac OS X to implement

00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:35.420
some of the behaviors that are
available to you on Mac OS X.

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:39.060
First of all, one of the unique behaviors
of Mac OS X is the dock.

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:41.580
The dock is there at the bottom of the
screen or on the left or the right.

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:45.480
And it has, as a developer,
you have some responsibilities

00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:46.870
around working with the dock.

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:49.320
There are three things that
you can do with the dock.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:54.710
Two that you should do,
and one that some applications might do.

00:15:56.130 --> 00:15:58.760
First of all,
every application on the platform--

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:02.240
and this is almost a basic,
but I didn't put it in that section--

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:06.500
every application on the platform should
respond to doc clicks appropriately.

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:08.400
If your application icon
is clicked in the doc,

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:10.520
you should always produce a window.

00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:13.780
If you're a document-based application,
bring forward a new untitled

00:16:13.780 --> 00:16:17.020
document if there are no documents
currently open in your application.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.270
If you're a document-based application,
but all of your document windows

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:23.060
are currently minimized to the doc,
then you should bring up the

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:26.120
last minimized document window,
because that's likely the one

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:28.540
the user was-- that's the one
they were last working in.

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:31.680
That's likely the one they
probably want to work in now.

00:16:31.770 --> 00:16:33.570
And if you're a
non-document-based application,

00:16:33.620 --> 00:16:36.360
say you're in iTunes or a system
prefs or something like that

00:16:36.360 --> 00:16:39.050
where you have a main window,
then if that window is currently

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:41.990
closed but your app is running,
you should bring that

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:43.870
window up and activate it.

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:46.690
Respecting the doc's location.

00:16:46.710 --> 00:16:48.500
As I said before,
the doc can be at the bottom of the

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:49.750
screen or on the left or the right.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:51.000
Who knows where it'll be in the future?

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:51.540
I don't know.

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:53.300
I'm not on the design team,
but who knows?

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:54.720
At the moment, it's in these locations.

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:59.200
And as your application windows,
as you open new untitled document windows

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:03.610
or as the user resizes document windows,
you should always honor the doc's

00:17:03.610 --> 00:17:07.530
position and never allow the user
to resize their window behind the

00:17:07.530 --> 00:17:12.010
doc or never automatically resize a
new untitled window behind the doc.

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:16.480
And so in this particular example,
you'll see here's a document window from

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:21.750
IE that your window should open flush
to the menu bar at the top and flush

00:17:21.850 --> 00:17:26.220
to the doc if it's on the bottom or
flush to the bottom of the screen if the

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:28.810
doc isn't on the bottom of the screen.

00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:32.760
The APIs for that are
pretty straightforward.

00:17:32.830 --> 00:17:35.040
But remember,
the users can change the dock's location.

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:37.300
They can also change the dock's size.

00:17:37.340 --> 00:17:42.020
So if they've sized their window
and you've honored the dock,

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:46.000
and afterwards they resize the dock
to cover the grow box from the window,

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:46.880
let them do that.

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:49.530
Don't resize your windows
and move windows around based

00:17:49.530 --> 00:17:50.900
on the movement of the dock.

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:54.190
Once the users set the window size there,
and if they change the dock,

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:54.990
that's their choice.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.820
Let them change their environment
without adapting to it.

00:17:59.930 --> 00:18:03.060
Something some applications
should do is provide meaningful

00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:04.870
status information via the doc.

00:18:04.980 --> 00:18:06.620
We talked about this a
little bit in session one.

00:18:06.620 --> 00:18:08.180
I'm going to talk briefly about it here.

00:18:08.180 --> 00:18:10.660
But the idea is,
if there's meaningful information

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.980
you can provide to your users about
the progress of your application,

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:17.230
doing something it's doing,
or if you're a fax application

00:18:17.230 --> 00:18:20.890
and you're sending a fax in the
background or receiving a fax,

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:25.700
providing that kind of status information
or progress information through your

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:29.710
doc icon is really meaningful and
very subtle and yet very effective

00:18:29.860 --> 00:18:31.360
at communicating what's going on.

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:33.900
So for example,
with the mail icon in Mac OS X,

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:37.250
we badge it with a starburst that says,
"Hey,

00:18:37.250 --> 00:18:40.640
there's new mail." And if it's sitting
down in the doc and your doc is visible,

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.800
you see that and it's a really cool cue,
very soft cue, saying,

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:46.780
"There's new mail." And so you
don't have to switch the app to

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:48.660
look whether there's new mail.

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:50.690
So that's an example of what
we're talking about here.

00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:53.880
Providing meaningful status
information through your doc icon.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:55.780
And again, I would say,
think very carefully

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:56.800
about when you do this.

00:18:56.800 --> 00:18:58.410
The last thing you want
to have is the doc,

00:18:58.500 --> 00:19:00.210
you know,
animating or having all kinds of

00:19:00.210 --> 00:19:01.920
status stuff occurring constantly.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.910
But where appropriate, it's very,
very valuable.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.550
And to do this through Carbon,
it's just look for the APIs with

00:19:08.550 --> 00:19:11.700
"doctile," the terms "doctile" in them,
in those header files.

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:15.190
In Cocoa, it's "nsApplication,"
"setApplicationIcon."

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:19.020
Okay,
another behavior that's very specific

00:19:19.020 --> 00:19:22.930
to Mac OS X that's very cool and
very visible to product reviewers

00:19:22.940 --> 00:19:25.300
and to customers alike is Sheets.

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:28.090
Sheets are document
modal specific dialogues.

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:32.240
Use them wherever you have a
dialogue box whose contents affect

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:35.020
the currently active document.

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:37.060
So think about your product for a minute.

00:19:37.060 --> 00:19:38.360
Do you have active documents?

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:39.400
Do you have document windows?

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:39.760
Yes.

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:43.080
Do you have modal dialogues
that currently open up to affect

00:19:43.080 --> 00:19:44.220
the contents of that document?

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:46.860
If the answer is yes,
those are candidates for Sheets.

00:19:46.860 --> 00:19:51.020
And the cool thing about Sheets is
they really implement the principle

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:54.470
of modelessness well because
they attach themselves to the

00:19:54.570 --> 00:19:56.920
document title bar of that window.

00:19:56.920 --> 00:19:59.430
They move with that document around,
so they're clearly associated

00:19:59.430 --> 00:20:00.850
with the content that they affect.

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:02.740
And yet,
they allow you to continue working in

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:04.390
that application on other documents.

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:05.780
So they're only modal
to that application.

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:07.710
Not modal to the whole application.

00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:09.220
To that document, rather.

00:20:09.220 --> 00:20:11.700
Not modal to the whole application.

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:15.640
Another way that we've implemented
motorlessness in Mac OS X is drawers.

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:18.290
Again, we touched on some of this
content in session one,

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:22.230
but drawers are great for providing
often used controls that don't

00:20:22.230 --> 00:20:23.850
need to be visible all the time.

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:27.890
They're also great for enabling you
to provide additional functionality

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:29.640
closely related to the parent window.

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:33.060
So it's really not a sheet because it's
not a case where you go and you do it

00:20:33.100 --> 00:20:35.550
all the time and then you dismiss it.

00:20:35.600 --> 00:20:38.540
But drawers are there for stuff that
just sort of hangs around that's

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:41.390
sometimes meaningful to be there,
but sometimes it's not meaningful or not,

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:43.420
you know,
effective to be there necessarily.

00:20:43.420 --> 00:20:45.240
But it's great to have it there
because you can pull it out,

00:20:45.270 --> 00:20:47.580
do something you need to do,
and push it back.

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:50.650
So think about where you do that
kind of stuff and where this could

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:52.480
be useful and implement drawers.

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:56.530
I have the pleasure of announcing
that Carbon drawers are now available,

00:20:56.620 --> 00:20:57.720
effective in Jaguar.

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:02.320
And in the headers, macwindows.h,
just look for APIs that have

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:03.730
the word drawers in them.

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:06.740
And this is a big deal for
Carbon developers who have been

00:21:06.740 --> 00:21:07.660
waiting a long time for this.

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:09.840
So there's no excuse to not implement it.

00:21:09.860 --> 00:21:11.780
into the drawers now.

00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:14.530
Another behavior of
Mac OS X is Apple Help.

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:19.680
Apple Help is this really effective
way of delivering help content to

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:22.390
your users in a very rich manner.

00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:25.400
QuickTime is integrated,
AppleScript is integrated,

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:27.500
so your users can read
through your help and say,

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:29.420
"Well, okay,
show me," and you can control your

00:21:29.420 --> 00:21:31.400
application through an AppleScript.

00:21:31.450 --> 00:21:34.520
It's a really great way to
deliver rich help content.

00:21:34.690 --> 00:21:38.440
And we've actually extended
Apple Help in Jaguar to build on its

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:41.380
ability to deal with remote content.

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:44.770
So where we are currently with
Mac OS X One is that Apple Help can

00:21:44.850 --> 00:21:46.310
support remote content.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:49.390
So you know how you're developing
your product and you run out of,

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:52.440
basically the development team
is still working on some stuff,

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:53.400
but you've got to
freeze the help content.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:56.400
And yet you want to document the stuff,
but it's still changing.

00:21:56.400 --> 00:21:59.400
And so anyway,
we all understand that situation.

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:01.930
Apple Help lets you put some
of this help content out on one

00:22:01.930 --> 00:22:03.250
of your servers and go get it.

00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:06.720
The beautiful thing about Apple Help in
Jaguar is that now you don't need

00:22:06.940 --> 00:22:10.000
to know what the structure of
that help content is necessarily,

00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:12.890
because we retrieve the
remote index as well.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:18.510
So now you can add and remove help
pages on the fly as you change

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:22.000
your system or as you understand
or realize that your help content

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
could be restructured or something.

00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:27.000
So really great feature in
Apple Help now in Jaguar.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.910
Second thing is that Apple Help in
Jaguar is internet primary.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.470
In other words,
it's going to look to the internet for

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:34.520
remote content under the assumption
that the remote content is more up

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:38.000
to date than the current local files
that you installed with your product.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:38.600
So leveraging both of these means
that you can do a lot of things.

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:41.060
So leveraging both of these means
you can really deliver great,

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:43.160
really flexible help.

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:45.390
As well in Jaguar,
the Help Viewer has been

00:22:45.390 --> 00:22:48.270
enhanced significantly in
terms of its user experience.

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:49.840
You can now,
with the Help Viewer in Jaguar,

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:52.540
look at multiple help
books at the same time.

00:22:52.590 --> 00:22:54.410
So you can have multiple
windows looking at help.

00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:57.280
You can copy text from the Help Viewer.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:22:58.790
Lots of people are asking for that.

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:00.880
You can enlarge the font
display in the Help Viewer.

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:04.090
It's got a customizable toolbar,
just like the Finder in Mail.

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:07.490
So significant enhancements
to the usability of the

00:23:07.490 --> 00:23:09.950
Help Viewer in Apple Help.

00:23:11.950 --> 00:23:17.300
Choosing colors is always a complicated
process just by its very nature.

00:23:17.330 --> 00:23:21.150
And we've provided the system colors
window in Mac OS X that up until this

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:22.920
point has only been available to Carbon.

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:24.020
It's a Cocoa, sorry.

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:26.300
It's now available to Carbon in Jaguar.

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:29.950
And the beauty of it is that it
provides a consistent user experience

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:32.290
across frameworks for picking colors.

00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:35.320
If your application allows users
to choose colors in any way,

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:37.970
whether it's for, you know,
coloring text or some

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:42.220
background or whatever it does,
don't do your own color picker.

00:23:42.220 --> 00:23:44.100
The difficulty with doing
your own color picker is,

00:23:44.100 --> 00:23:45.550
means that it behaves differently.

00:23:45.550 --> 00:23:48.680
The user comes to it with an expectation
about how it's going to behave because

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:51.780
you might have used the standard,
you know, control to get there.

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:54.940
And suddenly what's revealed
is something very different.

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:57.460
It behaves different than
what they're used to.

00:23:57.470 --> 00:24:02.900
And the system colors window is the way
to provide for color picking on Mac OS X.

00:24:03.360 --> 00:24:05.680
File name extensions are on Mac OS X.

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:09.120
They're a way of enhancing
the file name to improve

00:24:09.160 --> 00:24:10.760
interoperability with other platforms.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:13.440
We have specific goals around
providing file name extensions.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:18.760
The thing I want to talk about is
that our goal with this is to maintain

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:21.890
the usability of the Macintosh,
or that the Macintosh is always known.

00:24:21.900 --> 00:24:24.540
And so when file name extensions
are entered by the user,

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:27.260
it's basically a what you see is
what you get kind of behavior.

00:24:27.260 --> 00:24:29.400
So if the user types an
extension on the file,

00:24:29.470 --> 00:24:31.630
a file name extension,
that file shows up with

00:24:31.630 --> 00:24:32.770
a file name extension.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:34.490
If they don't type the
file name extension,

00:24:34.710 --> 00:24:35.880
it doesn't have a file name extension.

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:39.040
It's appended by the application.

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:41.230
Specifically as it relates
to user experience,

00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:43.320
I want to talk about

00:24:43.390 --> 00:24:45.020
The fact that there are display names.

00:24:45.020 --> 00:24:49.340
File names aren't only what the file
system tells you they are anymore.

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:51.840
So historically you could
say to the file system,

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:55.230
what's the file name,
or what did the user choose,

00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:56.230
and you'd get a name back.

00:24:56.340 --> 00:25:02.470
Now, pay attention to Nav Services,
what it tells you in terms of the

00:25:02.470 --> 00:25:04.820
file extension being hidden or not.

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:05.930
It's going to give you that bit.

00:25:05.970 --> 00:25:07.450
It's also going to give
you the full file name.

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:10.050
And so if it's hidden,
show just the main file name.

00:25:10.060 --> 00:25:11.830
The save panels will
do that appropriately.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:15.330
But wherever you display a
file name in your application,

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:17.930
say you've got a list of files,
or you're providing detailed

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:21.970
status information about a file,
make sure that you display the users,

00:25:21.970 --> 00:25:24.210
the display name for that file.

00:25:24.240 --> 00:25:29.590
The user is explicitly chosen to either
hide or show the file name extension.

00:25:29.630 --> 00:25:31.330
Your application should honor that.

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:35.170
So if I have a document
called lettertomom.txt,

00:25:35.230 --> 00:25:37.940
but I've hidden the extension,
and as far as I'm concerned

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:40.730
it's just called lettertomom,
when I double click that document

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:43.580
and it opens up in the application,
the document title bar

00:25:43.580 --> 00:25:48.140
should say lettertomom,
not lettertomom.txt.

00:25:48.140 --> 00:25:51.410
So the APIs to use are
in Launch Services,

00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:55.240
lscopyDisplayNameForRef,
lscopyDisplayNameForURL.

00:25:55.480 --> 00:26:00.480
These are the APIs you should be using
to get the display name for a file.

00:26:01.900 --> 00:26:02.900
Speech.

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:06.210
You saw this stuff demoed
earlier on in session one.

00:26:06.370 --> 00:26:11.340
Speech is a big part of our
universal access story in Jaguar.

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:16.340
And so building on system controls
and doing things like that are going

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:17.900
to enable you to leverage speech.

00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:20.900
And you get a lot of stuff for
free with speech in Jaguar.

00:26:20.900 --> 00:26:24.320
And I would encourage you to attend
the speech session on Friday where

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:27.920
we're going to talk about how our
speech synthesizer can be improved

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:29.630
and made to sound really great.

00:26:29.630 --> 00:26:31.590
And our recognition is really strong.

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:34.900
Managing Contacts.

00:26:34.970 --> 00:26:39.170
Today, we all run multiple applications,
we all run multiple tools,

00:26:39.170 --> 00:26:42.070
and the reality is that if those
applications require a phone number

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:45.600
or an email address or whatever,
we rely on that application

00:26:45.610 --> 00:26:47.750
to manage those contacts.

00:26:48.410 --> 00:26:51.350
I'm sure all of you have experienced
the case where you're using an email

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:54.860
program and you've got all of your
contacts in there for their emails,

00:26:54.860 --> 00:26:57.430
but then you've got another personal
information management tool,

00:26:57.440 --> 00:27:00.940
or you've got some other thing where
you're doing mail merge or whatever,

00:27:00.940 --> 00:27:03.850
and all three of those products
or more are pulling from

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.080
different databases for contacts.

00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:09.310
Wouldn't it be great if all
of those applications used the

00:27:09.310 --> 00:27:11.170
same source of information?

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:14.320
So regardless of whether I was
sending an email or sending a fax

00:27:14.320 --> 00:27:19.260
or doing some other operation on
my machine with some other product,

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:22.380
that all of the context would
come from the same place.

00:27:23.110 --> 00:27:24.430
It's possible with Jaguar.

00:27:24.440 --> 00:27:26.500
Because with Jaguar,
we're introducing something

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:28.060
called Address Book Framework.

00:27:28.140 --> 00:27:31.740
It's a very simple framework
available to Carbon and Cocoa that

00:27:32.240 --> 00:27:37.200
enables you to build on a standard,
single, centralized database in the

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:39.600
system to manage people,
the contacts around,

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:41.200
and the information around people.

00:27:41.200 --> 00:27:45.740
So in terms of delivering a great
user experience with your product,

00:27:45.750 --> 00:27:49.210
and in terms of being a
great citizen on Mac OS X,

00:27:49.240 --> 00:27:52.740
this is one of the things that you should
consider building into your application.

00:27:52.740 --> 00:27:55.040
Not only does it deliver
a great user experience,

00:27:55.040 --> 00:27:59.240
but it means that you can focus on the
value add that your product provides,

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:02.240
which is the unique
capabilities that it has,

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:04.740
versus, "Oh, yeah,
we've got to write this context thing

00:28:04.740 --> 00:28:08.520
and deal with all the UI around that
and all the database management," right?

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:11.840
Take your development cycles
and put them on the things that

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:14.440
are unique to your company,
the value add you bring,

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:17.110
rather than trying to write a lot
of stuff that everybody else is

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:19.850
trying to write and ultimately
confusing and diluting the

00:28:19.860 --> 00:28:22.190
user experience for that stuff.

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:25.600
We talked about three
areas of responsibility.

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:28.000
We've talked about the basics
that you need to do for

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.190
delivering a product on Macintosh.

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:33.200
We've talked about the
behaviors of Mac OS X.

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:35.340
Now I want to talk about the
responsibilities you have in terms

00:28:35.350 --> 00:28:39.700
of being a good citizen around
the appearance for Mac OS X.

00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:42.680
First of all,
it's clear that Mac OS X delivers

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:46.140
icons in a way that the
Macintosh has never done before.

00:28:46.140 --> 00:28:50.570
Icons are rendered in
a high quality manner.

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:55.240
They communicate a lot about
what the application does.

00:28:55.270 --> 00:28:57.400
Your application icon should be the same.

00:28:57.430 --> 00:29:00.530
Last year we talked about
this idea of a tool and media.

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:03.640
There's this tool like a pen and
the media being a piece of paper.

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:07.040
And those two ideas in your
icon can communicate a lot about

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:09.700
what your application does.

00:29:09.890 --> 00:29:13.100
Not only should your icons be quality,
but the overall graphics of your

00:29:13.100 --> 00:29:14.940
application should be quality.

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:19.160
Think about taking the existing
graphics from your Mac OS 9 product,

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:21.880
or from your Windows product,
or from your Java product,

00:29:21.980 --> 00:29:24.940
taking those graphics and redoing
them to feel more like they

00:29:24.940 --> 00:29:26.470
belong in the world of Mac OS X.

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:30.230
Anti-alias text, soft edges,
removable black lines,

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:33.470
these kinds of things that
you'll see throughout the system.

00:29:34.850 --> 00:29:37.570
Speaking of anti-aliasing,
I want to talk about anti-aliased text.

00:29:37.650 --> 00:29:42.870
The appearance for Mac OS X is such that
the text everywhere is anti-aliased.

00:29:42.890 --> 00:29:45.930
If your product is running on Mac OS X,
all of your text should

00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:47.000
be anti-aliased as well.

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:50.220
If it isn't, your application stands
out and feels incomplete.

00:29:50.220 --> 00:29:52.460
We'll look at some examples.

00:29:53.080 --> 00:29:54.820
The right way to draw text,
it depends on which

00:29:54.820 --> 00:29:55.640
framework you're using.

00:29:55.640 --> 00:29:57.460
There are ways to do it
properly in Power Plant.

00:29:57.460 --> 00:30:00.830
There are ways, certainly Carbon has
multiple ways of doing it,

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:02.250
but if you're writing
directly to the toolbox,

00:30:02.340 --> 00:30:05.070
using the Appearance Manager APIs,
like Draw Theme Text,

00:30:05.070 --> 00:30:08.680
etc., are going to mean that your labels,
etc., are appearing properly.

00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:11.680
Using standard system controls are
going to mean that your controls,

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:15.020
the labels are drawn by the system,
so they're automatically going to appear

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:16.950
in the appropriate font face and size.

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:19.120
So anti-aliased text really matters.

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:23.200
And if you have content text
views within your documents,

00:30:23.200 --> 00:30:28.830
consider using MLTE views
or the ATSUI engine,

00:30:28.830 --> 00:30:32.230
which there are sessions
about here at WWC.

00:30:33.280 --> 00:30:35.230
So what I'm talking about in
terms of antialiased text is

00:30:35.230 --> 00:30:36.780
to not do something like this.

00:30:36.780 --> 00:30:38.840
Here we've got a window
from an application.

00:30:38.840 --> 00:30:41.920
For one thing,
it's got a scrolling area of text

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:45.020
that has a striped background,
which is not the appearance for Mac OS X.

00:30:45.020 --> 00:30:49.620
Lists and scrolling areas of text
in Mac OS X have a white background.

00:30:49.620 --> 00:30:53.280
So that's one difficulty
this developer had.

00:30:53.280 --> 00:30:56.150
The second is all of the text
is not antialiased and it's

00:30:56.250 --> 00:30:58.100
so small it's hardly readable.

00:30:58.100 --> 00:31:01.210
So everywhere we deliver
text in your application,

00:31:01.210 --> 00:31:02.940
it should be antialiased.

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:04.230
Thank you.

00:31:05.370 --> 00:31:07.690
Steve introduced this
idea of the metal window,

00:31:07.710 --> 00:31:09.480
metal for the rest of us.

00:31:09.750 --> 00:31:12.010
As all of you know,
Mac OS X delivers several

00:31:12.010 --> 00:31:14.090
of our applications,
or Apple delivers several

00:31:14.090 --> 00:31:16.300
of our applications with
a metal window appearance.

00:31:16.390 --> 00:31:22.630
We have iTunes, we've got DVD player,
QuickTime player, etc.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:25.570
And this metal window
is now available to you,

00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:27.620
the developer community, to use.

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:30.100
I'll talk about the APIs in a second,
but before I get there,

00:31:30.100 --> 00:31:34.160
I want to give you some guidance around
the usage of this type of window.

00:31:34.830 --> 00:31:40.920
Where Apple uses it is in the cases where
we have a single window application.

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:42.700
Think iTunes.

00:31:42.840 --> 00:31:44.250
There's a central window.

00:31:44.410 --> 00:31:46.410
That's where you focus all of your time.

00:31:46.750 --> 00:31:48.220
That's where we chose
to use a metal window.

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:52.210
Also, because it kind of reflects
a real world device in a way.

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:53.860
It's kind of like a player of music.

00:31:53.860 --> 00:31:55.670
Think about the QuickTime player.

00:31:55.840 --> 00:31:58.790
It's kind of like a little TV in a sense,
but it's not.

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:01.680
But it kind of mimics
a real world device.

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:05.920
Those are examples of where
you would use a metal window.

00:32:06.100 --> 00:32:09.060
The other guidance I would
give around that is that it's,

00:32:09.060 --> 00:32:11.050
it's, use it only,
use the metal appearance

00:32:11.050 --> 00:32:13.000
only for your main window.

00:32:13.080 --> 00:32:14.750
So if you think about iTunes again,
or if you're,

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:16.760
if you've got a PowerBook sitting
in front of you right now,

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:18.340
fire up iTunes, take a look at iTunes.

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:21.490
It opens, there are other dialogues
in iTunes for preferences,

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:23.880
etc., but those dialogues are fully Aqua.

00:32:23.880 --> 00:32:25.000
They're not metal.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.500
So if you're going to use
the metal window appearance,

00:32:27.500 --> 00:32:29.020
use it for the main window only.

00:32:29.020 --> 00:32:31.840
And all of your other dialogues,
supporting dialogues within

00:32:31.950 --> 00:32:33.720
your application should be Aqua.

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:38.240
So the way to do this in Carbon,
actually you can't do it in Carbon with

00:32:38.350 --> 00:32:40.820
the build we gave you yesterday,
but you'll be able to do it real soon,

00:32:40.830 --> 00:32:43.000
because we're still some
stuff being defined,

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:45.080
but it's a new window class
and we'll give you the

00:32:45.090 --> 00:32:46.330
details later in the headers.

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:50.400
And in Cocoa it's just a constant.

00:32:52.920 --> 00:32:54.920
Palette, layout, and appearance.

00:32:54.920 --> 00:32:58.090
There are tons of applications today that
ship on the Macintosh that have palettes.

00:32:58.090 --> 00:33:02.000
And there are lots of high-end
illustration tools and web

00:33:02.010 --> 00:33:06.180
design tools and lots of
applications that use palettes.

00:33:06.250 --> 00:33:09.180
Because the cool thing about palettes
is they remain on screen all the time.

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:11.160
They're easily accessible to the user,
therefore.

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:12.840
They don't take up much real estate.

00:33:12.840 --> 00:33:15.410
And so your application,
if you deliver palettes

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:18.000
within your application,
should adhere to these

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:19.740
kinds of guidelines as well.

00:33:19.740 --> 00:33:22.780
Make judicious use of real estate.

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:24.360
You don't want to take up lots of room.

00:33:24.360 --> 00:33:27.820
You want to use smaller
spacings and tighten things up.

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:32.150
But at the same time,
you don't want to do something like this,

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:32.150
which is--

00:33:32.330 --> 00:33:34.320
They've used standard controls.

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:35.640
Everything is truly Aqua.

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:40.330
The difficulty here is things are kind of
compressed and it seems somewhat messy.

00:33:40.340 --> 00:33:44.020
So remember,
if you're bringing things down in size,

00:33:44.090 --> 00:33:47.800
to continue using the small
version of Aqua controls,

00:33:47.800 --> 00:33:50.640
but also remember to focus
on the alignments and the

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:52.580
overall layout of the palette.

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:56.060
So what would this look like if it was
adhering to the Aqua layout guidelines?

00:33:56.420 --> 00:33:58.660
We've got more alignment of controls.

00:33:58.660 --> 00:34:01.560
We've reduced redundancy
in labels that were there.

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:05.730
We've used verticals or horizontal
separators to distinguish

00:34:05.730 --> 00:34:07.460
sections of this palette.

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:12.150
So it's pretty simple stuff, but again,
a beautiful tool to do this around,

00:34:12.150 --> 00:34:15.930
or a beautiful tool to use to
do this is Interface Builder.

00:34:17.710 --> 00:34:18.870
Alright, missing the basics.

00:34:18.920 --> 00:34:21.750
We talked about a section
earlier on which was the basics.

00:34:21.750 --> 00:34:25.400
I'm talking about here about the basics
for the appearance in the system.

00:34:25.950 --> 00:34:29.760
Here we've got an application,
and I see lots of difficulty with this,

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:32.900
particularly in Carbon applications
coming over from Mac OS 9.

00:34:32.900 --> 00:34:37.460
But also Carbon applications coming from
other platforms where the developer has

00:34:37.460 --> 00:34:40.900
leveraged Carbon to do the interface
because of the structure of their code.

00:34:40.900 --> 00:34:43.900
They've chosen to use
Carbon because it's easier.

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:45.900
And there's just some
real difficulties here,

00:34:45.900 --> 00:34:47.900
and I wanted to point
these out specifically.

00:34:47.900 --> 00:34:51.200
Here I've got a dialog that's got,
has no respect for the margins that

00:34:51.220 --> 00:34:54.610
we define in the Aqua guidelines,
so the tab panes are

00:34:54.670 --> 00:34:56.780
very close to the edges.

00:34:56.900 --> 00:35:00.070
We've got multiple tab rows,
although the second row is

00:35:00.070 --> 00:35:02.890
really an inner tab pane,
which is okay to do.

00:35:02.900 --> 00:35:04.830
We do it in System Preferences.

00:35:04.950 --> 00:35:08.350
But certainly it should be spaced
downwards and then inwards so that

00:35:08.490 --> 00:35:11.660
you know that it's a separate tab
pane within a larger tab pane.

00:35:11.900 --> 00:35:14.950
The buttons at the bottom are
being obscured by shadowing,

00:35:14.950 --> 00:35:17.650
so there's over-compositing
there of the tab panes.

00:35:18.030 --> 00:35:20.390
All of the text in the
dialog is non-antelious,

00:35:20.390 --> 00:35:21.890
and it's all Geneva 9.

00:35:21.890 --> 00:35:24.900
It's hard-coded font faces and sizes.

00:35:24.900 --> 00:35:28.970
And I see this a lot as
I review applications.

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:32.280
An interface like this, for example,
on your product is going to

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:35.240
mean that your users judge the
quality of your product based

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:37.300
upon what they see on the screen.

00:35:37.410 --> 00:35:40.520
You've put a lot of effort
into writing your code.

00:35:40.610 --> 00:35:41.780
You know it's great.

00:35:41.950 --> 00:35:44.600
You want the world to experience it.

00:35:44.790 --> 00:35:47.850
Spend the time to make a really
great interface on top of it,

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:51.740
to put a really great Aqua-compliant
interface that leverages sheets and

00:35:51.740 --> 00:35:54.780
drawers and speech and all of the
stuff that we're talking about today

00:35:54.780 --> 00:35:57.500
to really create a killer application.

00:35:57.520 --> 00:35:59.880
Because then the users
look at it and they go,

00:35:59.890 --> 00:36:02.380
wow, this is great,
and look what it does.

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:06.790
Most users really are not concerned
about what your product does.

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:09.470
I mean, they are concerned about that,
but primarily they're

00:36:09.470 --> 00:36:10.870
concerned with how it does it.

00:36:11.800 --> 00:36:15.320
What differentiates you from
your competition is ease of use.

00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:17.190
Think about iMovie.

00:36:17.200 --> 00:36:21.120
Before iMovie was on the scene,
it was really hard to just

00:36:21.590 --> 00:36:22.760
pick up and edit a video.

00:36:22.760 --> 00:36:27.420
We spent a lot of time thinking about the
interface around iMovie and how do we,

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:28.380
you know, who are users?

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:29.240
What are they doing?

00:36:29.240 --> 00:36:30.830
Remember we talked about
this stuff in session one.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:31.560
Who are users?

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:32.100
What are they doing?

00:36:32.100 --> 00:36:33.120
What do they need to accomplish?

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:36.470
Simplify, simplify,
simplify to the point where we've

00:36:36.550 --> 00:36:39.940
got this iMovie thing that people are
just looking at as an example and a

00:36:39.940 --> 00:36:44.830
benchmark for creating really highly
usable consumer-oriented products.

00:36:46.350 --> 00:36:50.040
Don't let your interface knock
you down in terms of the judgment

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:51.840
your users render upon you.

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:54.510
You spend a lot of time in your code.

00:36:55.070 --> 00:36:56.220
Group boxes.

00:36:56.340 --> 00:36:59.350
Aqua has a very distinct
appearance in Aqua,

00:36:59.350 --> 00:37:02.070
and we encourage the use of white space.

00:37:02.070 --> 00:37:03.400
We have margins in dialogs.

00:37:03.530 --> 00:37:07.800
We encourage spacing between groups
of items or a single separator bar.

00:37:07.800 --> 00:37:10.290
And group boxes are still
available in the toolbox.

00:37:10.350 --> 00:37:11.420
You can still do them.

00:37:11.420 --> 00:37:13.790
You can define them in Interface Builder,
etc.

00:37:13.860 --> 00:37:18.180
But I want to encourage you to
think about moving away from

00:37:18.200 --> 00:37:20.750
group boxes wherever you can.

00:37:20.760 --> 00:37:23.800
Moving away from them means your
interface is going to feel lighter.

00:37:23.910 --> 00:37:25.320
It's going to feel cleaner.

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:28.010
You can actually drop the side
and the bottom lines from group

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:31.720
boxes and have the very same effect
where you have stacked group boxes.

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:34.720
So here we've got a UI on 10.

00:37:34.750 --> 00:37:36.090
It's pretty good.

00:37:36.250 --> 00:37:38.870
It's got Aqua compliance, pretty much.

00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:41.180
The spacing around the edges of
the dialog is a little tight.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:43.700
But it's pretty much there.

00:37:43.760 --> 00:37:45.720
And yet there's group boxes everywhere.

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:48.450
So if we clean this up a little bit,
remove the group boxes,

00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:50.720
we can actually do single
horizontal separators.

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:54.330
We can use the combo box that
I introduced earlier to actually

00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:59.220
reduce the size of this dialog while
still providing the same functionality.

00:37:59.220 --> 00:38:01.310
So we're trying to provide
the widgets you need,

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:04.120
but if you use those widgets and
adhere to the layout guidelines,

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:07.720
etc., you can actually reduce your
dialogs in many cases and make them

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:13.200
more functional and tighter and yet feel
lighter and have more breathing room.

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:17.190
Here's an application that
another difficulty I see,

00:38:17.190 --> 00:38:20.590
which is where a developer sees
a need for something and they

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:21.940
choose to customize it somewhat.

00:38:21.940 --> 00:38:24.790
And so here the developer has
too many tabs for this dialog,

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:26.780
so they figured, oh, what the heck,
we'll throw a scroll bar

00:38:26.780 --> 00:38:27.890
above it and scroll the tabs.

00:38:27.980 --> 00:38:32.580
The fact of the matter is that it's
a non-standard way to do things,

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:36.340
and not to mention the fact that the
tabs themselves aren't Mac OS X compliant

00:38:36.340 --> 00:38:37.580
in terms of the appearance.

00:38:37.620 --> 00:38:42.850
And so as you clean this dialog up,
what you get is a slightly larger dialog,

00:38:42.860 --> 00:38:45.000
because in fact there was only
one tab that wasn't visible,

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.930
but for some reason the
dialog can't be resized.

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:50.240
I don't know why, it's just a dialog box.

00:38:50.300 --> 00:38:53.480
Think about your dialog boxes,
don't make them too small.

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:56.590
I see consistently small, tiny,
tiny dialogs where people

00:38:56.650 --> 00:39:00.180
have crammed stuff into,
and you ask the developer why,

00:39:00.180 --> 00:39:03.740
I ask them why, and they say, well,
that's the way it always was,

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:04.760
or whatever.

00:39:04.780 --> 00:39:07.620
The fact of the matter is
dialog boxes are modal in age.

00:39:07.620 --> 00:39:08.880
They're not just a product of nature.

00:39:08.880 --> 00:39:11.880
The user is focused on their
contents and they invoke them,

00:39:11.880 --> 00:39:14.640
they focus on their contents,
and they dismiss them,

00:39:14.770 --> 00:39:16.000
and then they're done.

00:39:16.140 --> 00:39:17.470
Mac OS 9-ish.

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:20.560
Bringing a product from Mac OS 9,
make sure its appearance

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:21.830
is Mac OS X completely.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:25.230
Aqua provides for a very
rich graphical environment.

00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:31.010
However, overuse of color and things too
tight together mean that it's

00:39:31.070 --> 00:39:32.880
just too visually stimulating.

00:39:32.880 --> 00:39:36.040
So in this case, I don't know,
there's just too much going on

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:39.790
even though it's fully compliant
with the appearance of Mac OS X.

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:44.770
The appearance for toolbars in
Mac OS X is a very clean approach,

00:39:44.770 --> 00:39:48.440
and the icons we use are high
quality in terms of their rendering.

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:53.340
The icons we provide are shortcuts to
things that are multiple clicks away,

00:39:53.340 --> 00:39:57.350
and so consider very carefully
what you put in your toolbars.

00:39:57.360 --> 00:40:01.360
Don't put every function of
your application as an icon,

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:02.900
represented as an icon in your toolbar.

00:40:02.900 --> 00:40:05.370
You'll just have overpopulation
of your toolbars.

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:08.110
Focus specifically on those
things that dramatically increase

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:09.400
the productivity of your users.

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:13.340
And I'm pleased to announce that,
