00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:30.490
PowerPlant,
one of its benefits is that it's started

00:41:30.490 --> 00:41:35.850
back in the system seven days and it's
maintained compatibility with each OS.

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:39.330
However, because of that compatibility,
it's sometimes easy to get

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:43.560
lazy and not update your user
interface for each system.

00:41:43.630 --> 00:41:47.010
And so, if you have a program now
that's running on Mac OS 9,

00:41:47.060 --> 00:41:49.460
it's actually pretty easy
to just flip the switch,

00:41:49.530 --> 00:41:53.060
make it a Carbon application,
and have it run on Mac OS X.

00:41:53.140 --> 00:41:56.190
However, it's not going to look right and
it's not going to be a good citizen.

00:41:56.260 --> 00:41:59.200
And here are just a few quick tips.

00:42:04.050 --> 00:42:07.770
Here are just a few quick tips of
what you can do to quickly update

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:11.780
your Power Plant applications to
have an Aqua-savvy appearance.

00:42:11.890 --> 00:42:15.540
First, make a new menu bar for Mac OS X.

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:20.300
On Aqua interfaces,
there's the application menu that

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:23.940
automatically puts a quit item
and a preferences item there.

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:27.250
On Mac OS 9 applications,
you probably had your quit

00:42:27.380 --> 00:42:29.920
item in your file menu,
and if you had a preferences item,

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:31.900
it was probably at the
bottom of your edit menu.

00:42:32.140 --> 00:42:35.240
If you don't update your menu bar,
when you port your

00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:38.560
application to Mac OS X,
those items will appear twice.

00:42:38.590 --> 00:42:41.660
You'll have two quit items,
and you'll have two preferences

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:42.920
items in your menu bar.

00:42:43.190 --> 00:42:46.340
Both items will still work,
but it looks sloppy and not polished,

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:47.860
and you won't be a good citizen.

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:50.440
The other thing is background colors.

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:54.400
On Mac OS X, the Aqua appearance,
the background cannot just be a color,

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:56.740
but it could be a pattern,
and the standard interface

00:42:56.740 --> 00:42:59.150
has the subtle gray stripes.

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:01.840
If you developed your application
for a platinum look on Mac OS X,

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:06.340
you probably set it up so that your
window had a light gray background

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:09.280
color set up as the window color table.

00:43:09.370 --> 00:43:12.890
If you do that on 10, it'll again,
you'll get that platinum look,

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:15.100
but you won't get the proper system look.

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:18.160
So use theme brushes,
and Power Plant provides classes for

00:43:18.170 --> 00:43:22.390
automatically setting up your window
so it uses a proper theme brush.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:25.200
and use the Aqua Savvy classes.

00:43:25.230 --> 00:43:29.130
So, there's a little bit of
discrepancy here in terminology

00:43:29.130 --> 00:43:30.200
between what John mentioned.

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:33.200
When John talked about standard controls,
he meant the controls

00:43:33.200 --> 00:43:34.810
provided by the toolbox.

00:43:34.930 --> 00:43:36.770
Power Plant,
because it's been around for so long,

00:43:36.870 --> 00:43:41.450
when it refers to standard controls,
it means the System 7 controls.

00:43:41.590 --> 00:43:43.040
You had four controls back then.

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:47.640
You had a button, checkbox, radio button,
pop-up menu, and that was it.

00:43:47.950 --> 00:43:50.420
When the Appearance Manager came out,
Power Plant introduced a

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:53.520
whole slew of new classes for
using the appearance controls.

00:43:53.560 --> 00:43:55.370
Those are the controls
you should be using.

00:43:55.440 --> 00:43:58.010
You should not be using the
standard button on Power Plant.

00:43:58.020 --> 00:44:00.860
You should be using the
Appearance Manager push button,

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:02.470
et cetera.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:07.820
Similarly for text,
Power Plant provided a caption text

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:10.760
that used drawing via Quick Draw calls.

00:44:10.770 --> 00:44:12.590
Don't use that on Aqua.

00:44:12.620 --> 00:44:16.470
Use either the static text control
or the theme text box so that

00:44:16.470 --> 00:44:18.700
you get proper anti-alias text.

00:44:18.890 --> 00:44:22.670
And if you want to use anti-alias
text also in your edited text boxes,

00:44:22.670 --> 00:44:25.870
use the MLTE pane rather
than the text edit based.

