line with real world objects.

00:55:09.240 --> 00:55:12.640
So our calendar really
has a calendar in it.

00:55:12.770 --> 00:55:14.280
Email has a big envelope in it.

00:55:14.430 --> 00:55:17.150
The slide deck for PowerPoint looks
like there's slides you can hold up

00:55:17.150 --> 00:55:20.110
and actually project to sort of convey
to people these are the functions that

00:55:20.130 --> 00:55:21.760
these documents are designed to be.

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:24.060
going to actually execute.

00:55:24.060 --> 00:55:28.220
In terms of low visibility
features that we knew were helpful,

00:55:28.220 --> 00:55:29.300
the view switcher.

00:55:29.300 --> 00:55:33.180
PowerPoint and Word both have a view
switcher that changes modes to allow you

00:55:33.190 --> 00:55:35.150
to do different kinds of work activities.

00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:37.280
Sadly,
they were kind of buried in the bottom

00:55:37.280 --> 00:55:40.200
left corner of the document window,
and they're kind of hard to find.

00:55:40.210 --> 00:55:42.760
So in 10,
we brought in a finder-like view

00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:45.600
switcher that punches those features out.

00:55:45.610 --> 00:55:48.400
People can see right away,
there are big clickable

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:50.590
buttons down there,
and they're much more successful

00:55:50.590 --> 00:55:52.580
at finding that feature.

00:55:52.580 --> 00:55:55.100
We even wanted to bring
Aqua to our product icons,

00:55:55.100 --> 00:55:55.460
though.

00:55:55.460 --> 00:55:58.940
We're definitely enhancing usability,
but we want things to look great.

00:55:58.940 --> 00:56:01.800
We want people to know that this
is a new suite of applications

00:56:01.850 --> 00:56:05.510
under a new operating system,
and we changed our icons so they had

00:56:05.510 --> 00:56:10.530
more depth and were more exciting,
more new, more fresh.

00:56:11.080 --> 00:56:14.920
But beyond the static visuals,
we wanted to take that language

00:56:14.920 --> 00:56:16.380
step a little bit further.

00:56:16.510 --> 00:56:18.380
So we introduced animation.

00:56:18.580 --> 00:56:22.110
Now, the formatting palette was something
we introduced in Office 2001 as well.

00:56:22.200 --> 00:56:24.430
Again, very popular feature and
we're very happy with it.

00:56:24.530 --> 00:56:28.680
But we have a slight problem if people
were trying to manage their windows,

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:32.310
there was a case where people would
hide the formatting palette because

00:56:32.380 --> 00:56:35.500
it was in their way and then they
couldn't find out where it went,

00:56:35.580 --> 00:56:36.840
as you can see here.

00:56:36.840 --> 00:56:40.260
So in Office 10,
we introduced animation so that when

00:56:40.670 --> 00:56:44.470
people close the formatting palette,
it genies into a toolbar

00:56:44.470 --> 00:56:46.300
and then genies back out.

00:56:46.390 --> 00:56:49.080
And this has greatly
enhanced the discoverability.

00:56:49.080 --> 00:56:52.180
We've also enhanced the formatting
palette with other animations,

00:56:52.180 --> 00:56:54.190
for example,
when you close and hide panes,

00:56:54.220 --> 00:56:56.890
and there's a lot more fun
stuff we can do in the future.

00:56:56.900 --> 00:57:01.030
Aqua also gave us the opportunity
to redefine our dialogues.

00:57:01.150 --> 00:57:03.520
You've seen a lot of examples
today about dialogues that

00:57:03.530 --> 00:57:06.200
didn't quite make sense and,
well, this is one of ours.

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:09.200
This is the FillFX dialogue.

00:57:09.430 --> 00:57:10.350
Kind of hard to follow.

00:57:10.650 --> 00:57:13.380
When we were moving over to 10,
we were also bringing in new features.

00:57:13.400 --> 00:57:16.630
So we took this as a good opportunity
to change the look of the dialogue

00:57:17.060 --> 00:57:18.440
so that it had a better flow.

00:57:18.610 --> 00:57:20.030
We didn't just aqua-fied it.

00:57:20.120 --> 00:57:24.590
To a many extents, we ma-ca-fied it so it
was much more usable.

00:57:25.310 --> 00:57:29.200
We also wanted to bring the key
components of Aqua to our feature set.

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:31.690
Beyond the user interface,
we wanted to embed it

00:57:31.830 --> 00:57:33.390
into the actual product.

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:35.560
Our graphics in 2001 were nice.

00:57:35.610 --> 00:57:37.000
Our charts looked nice.

00:57:37.070 --> 00:57:39.940
The problem is the edges are really,
really jagged.

00:57:39.940 --> 00:57:41.730
The transparency didn't work really well.

00:57:41.740 --> 00:57:45.060
And these were obvious clues
for us that in Office 10 we

00:57:45.060 --> 00:57:49.710
wanted to see anti-alias text,
anti-alias lines, transparency,

00:57:49.750 --> 00:57:51.170
and I think the results
speak for themselves.

00:57:51.300 --> 00:57:52.770
We had to use a lot of different
methods to create a much,

00:57:52.770 --> 00:57:53.480
much better chart.

00:57:53.650 --> 00:57:56.100
So, have we been successful?

00:57:56.250 --> 00:57:59.760
Well, the San Jose Mercury News thought
we were the best looking piece

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:01.600
of software they had ever seen.

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:05.380
From Wired,
they thought we were so pretty

00:58:05.380 --> 00:58:08.590
they didn't believe we were real.

00:58:08.860 --> 00:58:12.390
Steve Jobs asked for a round of
applause and said that Apple was

00:58:12.390 --> 00:58:15.120
thrilled with the application,
and we're thrilled to hear that.

00:58:15.140 --> 00:58:16.800
So, have we been successful?

00:58:16.800 --> 00:58:18.260
Well, there's been a payoff.

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:21.380
Eight hundred dialogues later,
five hundred icons later,

00:58:21.380 --> 00:58:24.560
we have a great looking product,
and we're very proud of it.

00:58:24.560 --> 00:58:26.030
And the reviews have
been very motivational,

00:58:26.110 --> 00:58:27.480
certainly for our team.

00:58:27.560 --> 00:58:31.170
It's great to get up in the morning
and fire up your browser and read

00:58:31.170 --> 00:58:34.220
these great reviews from people who
really enjoy the work you're doing,

00:58:34.220 --> 00:58:37.370
and then they're getting to use your
product and enjoying it even more.

00:58:37.490 --> 00:58:39.500
And, of course, it translates into sales.

00:58:39.500 --> 00:58:41.510
The more people are
excited about your product,

00:58:41.580 --> 00:58:43.110
the more they're going to
want to go out and try it,

00:58:43.190 --> 00:58:46.810
especially as momentum builds more
and more and more behind OS X and,

00:58:47.170 --> 00:58:49.560
hopefully, Office 10 along with it.

00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:52.520
So beyond that even,
it's also sparking ideas

00:58:52.550 --> 00:58:54.110
for our next revisions.

00:58:54.320 --> 00:58:57.880
We've been very successful adopting
the language of Aqua in Office 10,

00:58:57.880 --> 00:58:59.750
but there's a lot more we can do,
and we're thinking

00:58:59.750 --> 00:59:02.700
about this all the time,
so we're really thrilled with it.

00:59:02.890 --> 00:59:03.700
Thanks, John.

00:59:04.040 --> 00:59:10.330
Great, thank you.

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:17.840
Next,
I'd like to invite on stage Ivor Clarke,

00:59:17.970 --> 00:59:21.590
who's president of Simple Factors,
a design agency working with

00:59:21.590 --> 00:59:23.640
a company called Media Maker.

00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:29.540
Thanks, John.

00:59:29.540 --> 00:59:31.380
So as John said, my name's Ivor Clarke.

00:59:31.540 --> 00:59:33.400
I'm president of Simple Factors.

00:59:33.540 --> 00:59:36.110
I'm here to talk to you a
little bit about the work my

00:59:36.110 --> 00:59:37.980
company did with MeetingMaker.

00:59:38.030 --> 00:59:40.200
First of all, a little bit of background.

00:59:40.230 --> 00:59:42.040
MeetingMaker,
for those of you who don't know,

00:59:42.060 --> 00:59:44.730
is a collaborative
scheduling application.

00:59:44.730 --> 00:59:47.210
It's been around for
a fair amount of time.

00:59:47.250 --> 00:59:48.980
It's about 12 years old.

00:59:48.980 --> 00:59:50.450
They're on version 7.

00:59:50.550 --> 00:59:52.530
It's one of the original applications.

00:59:52.530 --> 00:59:55.920
There's a lot of stuff that's
been hanging around there.

00:59:55.940 --> 01:00:00.750
And they're now engaged in a
two-part release strategy for OS X.

01:00:00.990 --> 01:00:03.740
The first is to get out a
version that is carbonized,

01:00:04.120 --> 01:00:06.420
works on OS X, gets full functionality.

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:08.800
It's what everyone's been clamoring for.

01:00:08.800 --> 01:00:11.880
And the second is to really
take advantage of it and knock

01:00:12.170 --> 01:00:15.300
-- take advantage of Aqua,
take advantage of the operating system,

01:00:15.310 --> 01:00:17.460
and really knock a
release out of the park.

01:00:17.460 --> 01:00:20.360
The first portion of that was
released just a couple weeks ago.

01:00:20.360 --> 01:00:22.970
That's version 7.1.

01:00:23.570 --> 01:00:26.670
My company, Simple Factors,
was brought in to assist in the designing

01:00:26.680 --> 01:00:30.150
of version 8 just a short while ago.

01:00:30.520 --> 01:00:33.740
So, before we talk about anything else,
the question is, why bother?

01:00:33.740 --> 01:00:36.120
They've got a release
that's fully carbonized.

01:00:36.290 --> 01:00:37.800
All the functionality works.

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:41.250
You might as well say, job done.

01:00:41.250 --> 01:00:43.060
Why move forward?

01:00:43.060 --> 01:00:46.100
Well, first of all, customer feedback.

01:00:46.100 --> 01:00:51.790
When we started designing version 8,
Aqua had been out for two years.

01:00:51.790 --> 01:00:55.310
Customers are really starting to
expect that of an OS X application.

01:00:55.330 --> 01:00:57.170
OS X is not about multitasking.

01:00:57.170 --> 01:00:59.110
It's not about multithreading.

01:00:59.150 --> 01:01:00.460
It's becoming about Aqua.

01:01:00.460 --> 01:01:03.740
It's becoming about a
great user experience.

01:01:04.170 --> 01:01:05.730
Second of all, it's a way to get noticed.

01:01:05.860 --> 01:01:08.900
What you saw from Stuart's presentation,
there are,

01:01:08.990 --> 01:01:13.060
when you do a great job with Aqua,
the press and others are going

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:14.940
to stand up and take notice.

01:01:15.380 --> 01:01:18.330
It's also an opportunity
for bigger changes.

01:01:18.680 --> 01:01:20.730
As you're going in,
making the changes to make

01:01:20.740 --> 01:01:23.320
a great looking application,
making the changes to

01:01:23.350 --> 01:01:26.950
take advantage of Aqua,
you have the opportunity to really get

01:01:27.080 --> 01:01:30.730
in there and reevaluate some of the
ways you present your user interface.

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:33.430
As I said, Meeting Maker had been
around for 12 years.

01:01:33.550 --> 01:01:37.640
This was an opportunity for
us to go in and ask ourselves,

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:40.230
were we really doing some
of the right things with the

01:01:40.230 --> 01:01:42.170
fundamentals of the application?

01:01:42.840 --> 01:01:45.240
And finally, other platforms.

01:01:45.320 --> 01:01:46.890
There are some other platforms out there.

01:01:46.910 --> 01:01:48.690
Meeting Maker ports to them.

01:01:48.720 --> 01:01:54.450
And they are also, some of them,
starting to put an emphasis on

01:01:54.450 --> 01:01:56.460
the visuals of the applications.

01:01:56.650 --> 01:02:00.950
And trust me, the work you do to create a
great-looking Aqua app will not be

01:02:01.090 --> 01:02:03.620
lost when you move to other platforms.

01:02:04.010 --> 01:02:05.900
So where did we focus?

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:09.640
We didn't work to take the
list of Aqua features and

01:02:09.640 --> 01:02:12.050
just sort of make a checklist.

01:02:12.350 --> 01:02:14.310
Instead, we said, well,
what is Aqua about?

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:15.430
There are a couple things.

01:02:15.590 --> 01:02:16.640
First of all, look and feel.

01:02:16.660 --> 01:02:21.230
I think this is what most
people associate with Aqua.

01:02:21.290 --> 01:02:26.230
It's that high production value,
great presentation.

01:02:26.320 --> 01:02:27.140
But it's more than that.

01:02:27.140 --> 01:02:30.140
It's more than just pulsating buttons.

01:02:30.140 --> 01:02:33.120
It's also a way to improve
feedback for the user.

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:37.190
When you look at the Dock,
the Genie effect, Sheets,

01:02:37.290 --> 01:02:41.960
all of those are ways to tie
what's going on in the system to

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:43.800
an action that the user has taken.

01:02:43.800 --> 01:02:47.800
And it really helps reinforce
those actions for the user.

01:02:47.800 --> 01:02:50.360
And finally, information presentation.

01:02:50.360 --> 01:02:53.380
One of the reasons Aqua looks great
is because it does a great job of

01:02:53.380 --> 01:02:55.550
presenting the user's information.

01:02:55.550 --> 01:02:58.580
If you take a look at the
column view in the finder,

01:02:58.580 --> 01:03:02.590
that's the same type of information
shown in the list view or finder view,

01:03:02.590 --> 01:03:06.400
but they've taken the opportunity to find
a better way to present that information,

01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:10.160
and I think it's what many people
are finding the most useful.

01:03:10.360 --> 01:03:11.580
So I want to walk through
a couple examples.

01:03:11.580 --> 01:03:15.280
This is the contact window.

01:03:15.280 --> 01:03:18.940
And when we were looking at aquifying it,
there's nothing fundamentally

01:03:18.950 --> 01:03:19.580
wrong with this.

01:03:19.580 --> 01:03:20.480
You can see everything.

01:03:20.480 --> 01:03:24.040
We could have just put a striped
background behind it and called it done.

01:03:24.040 --> 01:03:26.590
But we wanted to do a
little bit more than that.

01:03:26.640 --> 01:03:30.240
And this really goes to improving
information presentation.

01:03:30.240 --> 01:03:33.660
Rather than just changing
all the controls,

01:03:33.660 --> 01:03:35.620
we also looked at how the
information was organized.

01:03:35.620 --> 01:03:36.940
We looked at how it was presented.

01:03:36.940 --> 01:03:39.440
And what we ended up with
is something that not only

01:03:39.440 --> 01:03:43.060
looks a lot better under OS X,
but it does a much better job

01:03:43.080 --> 01:03:45.180
of presenting the information
and becomes more usable.

01:03:47.130 --> 01:03:48.740
This is the Proposals window.

01:03:48.860 --> 01:03:52.560
This is where you see proposals
from other users for meetings or

01:03:52.610 --> 01:03:56.440
invitations that you've sent to other
users for meetings you've created.

01:03:56.560 --> 01:04:01.130
Now, we could have, again,
just put some new toolbar icons in,

01:04:01.220 --> 01:04:06.130
improved the title bar, scroll bar,
that kind of thing.

01:04:06.510 --> 01:04:09.580
But instead, we again re-evaluated what
type of information do we

01:04:09.580 --> 01:04:10.690
need to present to the user?

01:04:10.740 --> 01:04:11.800
How can we make it look better?

01:04:11.800 --> 01:04:15.160
Yes, we've got the new icons,
and we've got the new controls,

01:04:15.290 --> 01:04:17.400
but we also looked at the
types of information that are

01:04:17.510 --> 01:04:18.720
required for the user here.

01:04:18.860 --> 01:04:21.700
We gave them a little extra data,
and in doing so,

01:04:21.780 --> 01:04:25.340
allow them to make better decisions
when they're using the product.

01:04:25.780 --> 01:04:27.730
So this is the schedule window.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:31.710
The schedule window is used to

01:04:32.110 --> 01:04:36.450
Pick a time for your meeting based
on your guests' availability.

01:04:36.470 --> 01:04:40.240
So if you see that red
stripe on the left-hand side,

01:04:40.240 --> 01:04:43.240
that's the availability
of all your users.

01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:46.260
It shows when they're all
busy or when they're all free.

01:04:46.300 --> 01:04:49.950
Well, that can be a little limiting when
you're trying to make a decision

01:04:50.360 --> 01:04:53.330
about when to have a meeting.

01:04:53.430 --> 01:04:58.400
So when we redesigned it,
not only did we use Apple's

01:04:58.700 --> 01:05:01.680
dialog layout guidelines,
use new controls,

01:05:01.850 --> 01:05:05.980
make sure the presentation was right,
but we also added extra information.

01:05:06.010 --> 01:05:10.200
Now you can see on a case-by-case
basis whether a user is available.

01:05:10.250 --> 01:05:13.040
You'll also notice that
yellow transparent stripe,

01:05:13.040 --> 01:05:15.180
that shows your chosen meeting time.

01:05:15.200 --> 01:05:18.050
We took advantage of some
OS X technologies to use

01:05:18.050 --> 01:05:21.840
transparency to improve the ability
to see whether the meeting time

01:05:21.840 --> 01:05:23.300
you've chosen conflicts with anyone.

01:05:23.300 --> 01:05:24.300
Thank you.

01:05:25.470 --> 01:05:28.510
So,
my final example really touches on that

01:05:28.750 --> 01:05:31.800
piece of improving feedback to the user.

01:05:31.830 --> 01:05:35.660
This is the dialogue you go to when you
want to change the view of your calendar,

01:05:35.660 --> 01:05:37.420
change the appearance of your calendar.

01:05:37.420 --> 01:05:40.540
So you can change some fonts here,
some other stuff.

01:05:40.600 --> 01:05:42.920
But of course what you have to
do is look at your calendar,

01:05:42.940 --> 01:05:45.930
imagine what you want,
go to this dialogue, make the changes,

01:05:45.930 --> 01:05:47.750
click OK,
then go back and see if what you

01:05:47.830 --> 01:05:50.160
changed is actually what you wanted.

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:51.680
Hope you're right.

01:05:51.680 --> 01:05:54.600
So instead, we just tie it in directly.

01:05:54.670 --> 01:05:57.360
As the user's make the
changes to colors and fonts,

01:05:57.360 --> 01:06:00.420
they see them reflected
directly in the calendar.

01:06:00.420 --> 01:06:03.930
And then when they go back,
it's going to be exactly

01:06:03.930 --> 01:06:05.420
what they wanted.

01:06:06.210 --> 01:06:07.340
Finally, reaction.

01:06:07.390 --> 01:06:10.420
Now, as I mentioned,
this product has just started

01:06:10.420 --> 01:06:13.140
the development phase,
but already we've begun to

01:06:13.140 --> 01:06:14.960
share it with customers.

01:06:15.040 --> 01:06:18.170
First of all,
there's an enormous amount of

01:06:18.180 --> 01:06:20.490
energy in the organization.

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:23.250
The development team is getting
really psyched about developing this.

01:06:23.320 --> 01:06:25.970
The test organization can't
wait to start testing it.

01:06:26.060 --> 01:06:29.670
Sales is already seeing this as
a huge opportunity to go out and

01:06:29.670 --> 01:06:32.760
sell a new product to customers.

01:06:32.820 --> 01:06:36.050
And customers are really,
really liking what we're showing them.

01:06:36.180 --> 01:06:37.690
They see we're taking Aqua seriously.

01:06:37.700 --> 01:06:40.220
They see we're taking OS X seriously.

01:06:40.280 --> 01:06:44.360
And they also see us really putting an
emphasis on what's important to them.

01:06:44.390 --> 01:06:46.290
I mean,
administrators are the people who have

01:06:46.290 --> 01:06:50.220
to take care of this in an organization,
so it can cost them a lot of money

01:06:50.220 --> 01:06:52.000
if the product's hard to use.

01:06:52.050 --> 01:06:55.110
They see us taking usability
of the product seriously,

01:06:55.110 --> 01:06:56.980
and they really like what we're doing.

01:06:57.070 --> 01:07:00.520
That's pretty much all I've got,
and I'll hand it back over to John.

01:07:05.470 --> 01:07:07.010
Great, thank you Ivor.

